<HEAD>$510 Million Lawsuit Filed In Wake Of Social Club Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An illegal social club served alcohol without a
license to an already-drunk man who is accused of killing 87 people
when he torched the place, a $510 million lawsuit says.
   The lawsuit was filed Thursday as relatives and friends of
victims held funerals and wakes, and as the accused, Julio
Gonzalez, appeared in Bronx Criminal Court for a hearing.
   About 1,000 mourners gathered Thursday night outside Ortiz
Funeral Home in the Bronx for the wakes of six victims of the Happy
Land Social Club fire.
   ``We want justice,'' said Edith Melendez, the girlfriend of Luis
Drummond, who died in the fire Sunday. ``Give him (Gonzalez) to us.
We could take him to the park, pour some gasoline on him like he
did to our family and friends.''
   The suit was filed in Bronx state Supreme Court, New York's
trial-level court, by attorney Harry Lipsig on behalf of Jennie Mae
Danzler, mother of another fire victim, 31-year-old Natalie Danzler.
   The suit names as defendants the social club itself; Clarendon
Place Corp., owner of the premises; Little Peach Realty, lessee;
Alex DiLorenzo III, Jay Weiss and Morris Jaffe, officers of Little
Peach; Elena Colon, widow of club owner Elias Colon, who died in
the fire; and Gonzalez. Weiss is the husband of actress Kathleen
Turner.
   The suit seeks $10 million in compensatory damages and $500
million in punitive damages. It claims, among other things, that
Happy Land served alcohol without a license and served it to
Gonzalez when he already was intoxicated.
   Authorities Thursday continued to crack down on illegal social
clubs, with more than 100 police officers transferred from the
Tactical Narcotics Teams to a reactivated Social Club Task Force.
